\subsection{Existence, Uniqueness, and Invariance}

The right-hand side of the system $(\ref{eq:dVdt})$--$(\ref{eq:dxdt})$ is locally Lipschitz on
$\mathbb{R} \times [0,1]^3$.
Thus, by the Picard--Lindel√∂f theorem,
a unique local solution exists for all initial conditions.

Positivity invariance holds:
\[
x(0)\in[0,1]\quad \Rightarrow\quad x(t)\in[0,1],\;\forall t\ge 0,
\]
because the vector field points inward at boundaries.

\subsection{Analytical Result: Depolarization Block}

At depolarized resting potential $V_{\mathrm{rest}}=-40\,\mathrm{mV}$, the corrected inactivation gate fulfills:
\[
h_\infty(-40) \approx 0.0018.
\]

Thus,
\[
m^3 h \approx 0,
\]
preventing the sodium current from generating an action potential.  
Therefore, stimulus-induced spike initiation fails:
\[
\max_t V(t) \approx -54.4\,\mathrm{mV}.
\]
This reproduces the classical depolarization block phenomenon observed in channelopathy and high-frequency failures.

